50|$|Dichlorine trioxide, Cl2O3, is a <b>chlorine</b> <b>oxide.</b> It is a {{dark brown}} solid {{discovered}} in 1967 which is explosive even below 0 °C. It is formed by the low-temperature photolysis of ClO2 and is formed along with Cl2O6, Cl2 and O2. Its structure {{is believed to be}} OCl-ClO2 with possible isomers such as Cl-O-ClO2. It is the theoretical anhydride of chlorous acid.|$|R
